Overtime work is allowed in several situations:

* During times of war or declared emergencies (Article 89(a));
* To prevent loss of life or property or ensure public safety due to accidents, fires, floods, etc. (Article 89(b));
* For urgent machine maintenance to avoid significant losses (Article 89(c));
* To protect against loss or damage to perishable items (Article 89(d)); and
* When completing tasks begun within the initial 8 hours would hinder business operations significantly (Article 89(e)). 

Additionally, employees can also work extra hours after being trained through programs like those mentioned in Articles 83-85, however these articles were omitted here so I am unable to provide further information about them. However they do state that certain conditions must be met prior to allowing extended shifts.

The just causes for termination by employer include:

* Serious misconduct or willful disobedience by the employee of the lawful orders of his employer or representative in connection with his work;
* Gross and habitual neglect by the employee of his duties;
* Fraud or willful breach by the employee of the trust reposed in him by his employer or duly authorized representative;
* Commission of a crime or offense by the employee against the person of his employer or any immediate member of his family or his duly authorized representatives;

(All under Art. 297.)

Separation pay refers to payment made to employees when they leave their job through termination, closure of establishments, reduction of personnel, etc. Under Articles 298, 299, it can range from one-month's worth of salary to half-a-month's wage per year of service, depending on circumstances like serious business loss or diseases affecting public health. 

A fraction of at least six months counts as one full year. For instance:

* One-month pay if terminated due to reasons except serious business losses;
* At least one-half month pay for each year served if closed or ceased operations were not because of severe economic reversals;

