According to Art. 259(a), it is an unfair labor practice for an employer to:

* Interfere with, restrain or coerce employees in the exercise of their right to self-organisation;
* Require as a condition of employment that a person or an employee shall not join a labour organisation or shall withdraw from one to which he belongs;

Also according to Art. 259(c):

* Contract out services or functions being performed by union members when such will interfere with, restrain or coerce employees in the exercise of their right to self-organisation;

And finally, according to Art. 259(d):

* Initiate, dominate, assist or otherwise interfere with the formation or administration of any labour organisation, including the giving of financial or other support to it or its organisers or supporters;

It is also mentioned in Art. 259(e)

* Discriminate in regard to wages, hours of work and other terms and conditions of employment in order to encourage or discourage membership in any labour organisation.

Authorized causes for termination include:

* Serious misconduct or wilfull disobedience by the employee (Art. 297);
* Gross and habitual neglect by the employee of his duties;
* Fraud or wilfull breach by the employee of the trust reposed in him by his employer or duly authorized representative;
* Commission of a crime or offence by the employee against the person of his employer or any immediate member of his family or his duly authorised representatives;
* And others analogous to these grounds (Art. 297).
Also, continued employment which is prohibited by law due to illness can also serve as ground for termination (Art. 299). 

Note: These provisions apply when there's a need to dismiss employees based on certain reasons allowed by labour laws. However, employers must follow proper procedures like giving adequate notices etc. mentioned elsewhere within PD 442.
